{
  "texts": [
    "It holds that, ∥T d (φ, ψ)∥ 2 HS -2⟨T d (φ, ψ), T ⟩ HS = E X E Z (φ(X) T ψ(Z)) 2 -2E X,Z [φ(X) T ψ(Z)].Proof.",
    "Let us introduceΦ: R d → L 2 (X), c → d i=1 c i φ i, Ψ: R d → L 2 (Z), c → d i=1 c i ψ i, such that T d (φ, ψ) = ΨΦ *, Ψ * Ψ = E[ψ(Z)ψ(Z) T] and Φ * Φ = E[φ(X)φ(X) T].On one hand, we have:∥T d (φ, ψ)∥ 2 HS = ∥ΨΦ * ∥ 2 HS = Tr (Ψ * ΨΦ * Φ) = Tr (E[ψ(Z)ψ(Z) T]E[φ(X)φ(X) T]) = E X E Z [Tr (ψ(Z)ψ(Z) T φ(X)φ(X) T)] = E X E Z (ψ(Z) T φ(X)) 2.On the other hand, we have:⟨T d (φ, ψ), T ⟩ HS = Tr (Ψ * T Φ) = Tr E ψ(Z)E [φ(X) | Z] T = E XZ [Tr (ψ(Z)φ(X) T)] = E XZ [ψ(Z) T φ(X)],which conclude the proof.As noted in [25], the above result does not require T to be Hilbert-Schmidt, or even compact.",
    "Indeed as T d (φ, ψ) is a finite rank operator, ⟨T d (φ, ψ), T ⟩ HS is always well defined.",
    "D Extended Related WorkWe now discuss the various ideas that have been proposed to solve NPIV problems.",
    "Extensive benchmarking for these methods has already been conducted in prior work; refer, for instance, to [36].As mentioned in Section 1, a central challenge in NPIV estimation is that it constitutes an ill-posed inverse problem."
  ]
